function longestObstacleCourse(obstacles) {
    const ans = new Array(obstacles.length), active = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < obstacles.length; i++) {
        const idx = upperBound(active, obstacles[i]);
        ans[i] = idx + 1;
        if (idx === active.length) {
            active.push(obstacles[i]);
        } else {
            active[idx] = obstacles[i];
        }
    }
    return ans;
}

function upperBound(arr, x) {
    let l = 0, r = arr.length;
    while (l < r) {
        const m = l + Math.floor((r - l) / 2);
        if (arr[m] <= x) {
            l = m + 1;
        } else {
            r = m;
        }
    }
    return l;
}
```

    The algorithm uses a dynamic programming approach to calculate the longest obstacle course. It keeps track of the active obstacle heights. 

1. Iterate through the input array from 0 to n-1.
2. For each obstacle, find its position (idx) in the active sequence using binary search.
3. Update the length of the longest obstacle course for the index i as (idx + 1).
4. If the idx is equal to the length of the active sequence, push the obstacle height to the active sequence, else update the active sequence at position idx with the current obstacle height.

This approach makes it possible to find the longest obstacle course in O(n log n) complexity.

